on-arrival: youth_dove += 3; consumer_democrat -= 2; consumer_dove += 2

As the dust begins to settle in Chicago, we choose to quickly organize a convention there for the nomination of Eugene McCarthy. However, we have a limited presence in Chicago, and without help organizing the convention from elements already there, we will face difficulty in our aims.

- @yippie: We will invite the Yippies to organize and participate in the convention.
- @progressive: We will invite the antiwar delegates from the Democratic Convention.
- @mobe: The Mobe and other antiwar groups active in the protests are our best bet.

@yippie
subtitle: Perhaps we can bridge the radical-moderate divide and unite the progressive movement.
on-arrival: dependence -= 2; independence += 6; consumer_democrat += 2; consumer_dove -= 4; workers_dove -= 1; youth_dove += 1; mccarthy_confidence -= 10

It takes some convincing to get the radical Yippies to agree, seemingly still intent on running a pig for office. However, with help convincing from moderate Phil Ochs, they eventually come around and agree that Eugene McCarthy makes just as fine a pig. They work quickly, rallying the protestors still in the city. When Eugene McCarthy arrives at the convention hall the Yippies have prepared, he is taken aback. Bedraggled protestors mill about, while posters line the walls with radical messaging emblazoned. The floor is lined with scattered underground newspapers, and ahead of him, the podium expected appears more of a soapbox. Before McCarthy can have second thoughts, he is greeted by Abbie Hoffman, who leads him in past the cheering attendees. The convention begins, and many speakers walk up to the soapbox, our Peace and Freedom delegates and Yippies alike, unsettling McCarthy further. Nevertheless, by the end of the day he is nominated, with, for better or worse, the noncommittal backing of the Yippies, whose ideas have entered the party discourse.

